        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "The Dem Bow Beat "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The predominant rhythmic orientation of reggaetón is derived directly from dancehall reggae. While there is also influence from roots reggae, dancehall's textures, tempos, rapid-fire flow, and minimalist focus on 3+3+2 cross rhythms demarcated by heavy, synthesized drums have had a stronger influence. One of the most enduring features is the following "
        },
        {
          "text": "riddim ",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "with"
        },
        {
          "italic": true,
          "text": " "
        },
        {
          "text": "a 4/4 pulse of a kick drum and syncopated snares audible in Shabba Ranks' song \"Dem Bow\" (1990). Below are song samples that help illustrate the prevalence of this riddim throughout reggaeton's development. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
